  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that “just adding more engineers” is a fallacy because the coordination cost of larger teams grows quadratically (n (n‑1)/2), quickly outweighing any gains in raw capacity. It cites classic research (Brooks’s *Mythical Man‑Month*, Microsoft DevDiv studies, *Accelerate*, and Amazon’s two‑pizza rule) to show that communication overhead, onboarding latency, and the “mentorship tax” make large teams slower, less reliable, and harder to ship on tight deadlines. The piece is aimed at engineering managers, VP‑level leaders, and senior developers who are tempted to scale staff to meet schedule pressure, and it adopts an analytical, slightly admonishing tone that repeatedly uses the “communication paths” metaphor and the O(n²) formula to frame its argument.",
